WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.960
Hi, sounds like my mic is working, okay great.

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:17.240
So yeah, my name is Carl Vogel, I'm a Principal Data Scientist at a company called BabyList.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:22.959
I am here to nominally talk about A-B testing.

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:26.480
This is the, you probably know by now, but this is how you ask questions, I'll try and

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:32.840
leave a minute at the end, otherwise feel free to accost me in the hallway.

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:40.720
But I'd like to start with a story, and in this story you are a data scientist, which

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:46.040
is hopefully not super hard to imagine, and you work at a company that sells goods or

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:51.959
services online, and one day a product manager comes up to you asking about a test they want

00:00:51.959 --> 00:00:54.560
to run for some feature they want to launch.

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:57.840
And this is not, this is like a substantial feature, it's not, we're not like moving a

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:02.439
button on the page somewhere, we're not like changing some copy, designers were involved,

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:05.919
engineers were involved, you know, this is part of like a broader user experience strategy

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:07.599
we're trying to do.

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:11.599
And you get like that perennial question, that perennial data question of like how much

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:17.800
data do I need for this, or in this case, how long should I be running this experiment?

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:22.480
And now you are a competent and like a diligent data scientist, hopefully that's also not

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.480
hard to imagine, and you ask some thoughtful questions about, well, what are you trying

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.639
to measure, and what does success and failure look like for this feature, and importantly,

00:01:31.639 --> 00:01:36.000
how big of a conversion lift are we looking to get here to make this worthwhile?

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.160
And the product manager sort of struggles with these questions a little bit, but you

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:43.040
get answers, and you run off and do the thing you were trained to do, and you do some sample

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:46.760
size and some power calculations, and you figure out an expected test length, and you

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:50.400
get back to them, and you say, well, you're going to need six weeks for this, to test

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:51.400
this feature.

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:58.120
And they go, that's great, thank you for this, we have budget appetite for two weeks.

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:02.599
And so you like take a deep breath, and you wish them well, and you warn them that they

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:06.959
may not be able to detect the kind of effects they're interested in in two weeks, and they

00:02:06.959 --> 00:02:11.119
seem oddly okay with that warning, they're like, okay, cool.

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:14.240
And two weeks pass, and you go take a look at the data, and like lo and behold, there

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:18.440
is a conversion lift in this new feature, and if it were real, it would mean meaningful

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:21.679
amount of money for the company.

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:25.119
But given the test length and sample size, it's not statistically significant, and you

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.279
go back, and you report this to them, and they respond to you with three words.

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:34.800
And now you have maybe studied and applied experimental methods for a long time, for

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.440
many years, and you have never heard these three words before, but they're called launch

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:41.880
on neutral, or maybe they said launch on flat.

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.160
But either way, it basically means, hey, I heard you, it's not statistically significant,

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:49.360
but it's positive, and I'm going to launch the feature anyway.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:56.559
And you respond, you know, you have a very logical response to this, right?

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:00.960
But you are introspective, and you are curious, and when you are done raging about the lack

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:06.600
of respect for type one error rates or whatever, you start asking stakeholders, hey, what's

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:07.600
the deal?

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:08.600
Why do we do this?

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:13.880
Why do we run an underpowered test, and then launch on an insignificant result?

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:16.479
If you're like me, you might get answers kind of like this, right?

00:03:16.479 --> 00:03:20.320
You're going to hear about some faith in a broader strategy, or wanting to launch something

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:22.679
and learn and iterate on it, and all this stuff.

00:03:22.679 --> 00:03:27.160
And this will start to make you think about A-B testing in your organization a little

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:32.479
bit differently, as something that has attributes that make it distinct from the raw application

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:36.919
of null hypothesis significance testing, right?

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:40.800
And some of these attributes are that, you know, the features we test are not just coming

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.240
off of a conveyor belt, like randomly drawn out of a population of ideas that might make

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:47.720
us money, might lose us money, who knows, right?

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:48.919
They are carefully planned.

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:49.919
They are roadmapped.

00:03:49.919 --> 00:03:53.520
They have a lot of path dependencies between each other.

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:58.399
You know, one, what we do in the next feature depends on what we see in this one, and all

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:00.240
this sort of stuff, right?

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:04.479
Secondly, we always struggle to have these conversations about sample size and test design

00:04:04.479 --> 00:04:08.080
with folks, because you need some effect size input into it, and they always struggle to

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.080
tell you that.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:12.639
And that's because by the time we have gotten to the test, we have sunk all the cost of

00:04:12.639 --> 00:04:13.639
deploying the feature.

00:04:13.639 --> 00:04:15.679
It is basically pushing a button at that point.

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:17.079
So any lift is good.

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:18.079
Any lift is cool.

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:21.600
Let's do that, right?

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:25.959
And we're, like, talking to them in these terms of, like, type 1 and type 2 error rates,

00:04:25.959 --> 00:04:29.200
and this is just, like, doesn't correspond to how, like, these decision makers are thinking

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:31.160
about the risk in this decision.

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.799
They just kind of, like, want to make more money than they lose on average, and, like,

00:04:34.799 --> 00:04:37.160
never lose too much money at a time.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:41.000
It's really hard to, like, map this to, like, the false positive and false negative rates

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.559
conditioned on, like, a null hypothesis, right?

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:49.500
They are asking us this question, essentially, right?

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.359
How do I make a good decision about the effect size I see?

00:04:52.359 --> 00:04:55.559
And we are handing them some tools that go, well, here are some statistical guarantees

00:04:55.559 --> 00:04:57.119
on an inference you might want to make.

00:04:57.119 --> 00:05:02.679
And so there's a little bit of a mismatch, and they end up misusing the tools or ignoring

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:06.559
the tools, and this is kind of what this talk is about.

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:12.040
When we see this happening, the instinct is kind of, like, correct their use of the tool,

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:15.440
but I want to argue in the A-B testing context, we maybe want to think about handing them

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:17.959
slightly different tools.

00:05:17.959 --> 00:05:23.600
And so for the rest of my time, I am going to talk about two approaches to thinking about

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.720
an A-B test that have helped me have, like, more productive conversations with decision

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:31.619
makers.

00:05:31.619 --> 00:05:37.859
So the first approach is non-inferiority test designs, which are not new and not esoteric,

00:05:37.859 --> 00:05:43.420
but I think they're slept on in the A-B testing context a little more than they ought to be.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:49.920
You'll notice the picture here is a guardrail, and that's the metaphor to keep in mind.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:53.700
The main idea of this approach is that instead of testing whether the new version of the

00:05:53.700 --> 00:05:57.480
site is better than the current one, we're just going to test whether it's not worse

00:05:57.480 --> 00:05:59.179
by some margin.

00:05:59.179 --> 00:06:05.779
And that margin is the delta in the red box there, and we call that the inferiority margin.

00:06:05.779 --> 00:06:06.779
What is this bias?

00:06:06.779 --> 00:06:11.619
Well, when you have a conversation about what these margins ought to be, you are forcing

00:06:11.619 --> 00:06:15.940
conversations about the sort of things that motivate these, like, launch on neutral type

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:20.059
decisions about, you know, well, how much do you want to risk to launch this thing?

00:06:20.059 --> 00:06:21.420
How much do you believe in it?

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:24.859
How quickly are you going to iterate on it and improve on it after it's launched, right?

00:06:24.859 --> 00:06:28.119
And stakeholders can kind of start to give you, like, meaningful answers to these questions

00:06:28.119 --> 00:06:32.839
instead of coming up with a fake effect size that they want to find.

00:06:32.839 --> 00:06:36.799
And you can start to power against this, like, well, any positive effect is good type of

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:39.679
scenario.

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:40.679
And you see that.

00:06:40.679 --> 00:06:42.040
That's kind of what this graph does here.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:46.119
And you can start to have a conversation about, well, look, if you run a test for three weeks

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:51.559
and you want good power against any feature that, like, isn't losing us money, then you

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:57.239
may have to accept some small risk that it actually will lose us, like, say, 1.5% conversion

00:06:57.359 --> 00:06:58.959
drop, right?

00:06:58.959 --> 00:07:00.440
And maybe that's an acceptable risk.

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:01.880
Maybe it's not an acceptable risk.

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:05.880
But it's an assessment of risk that usually they can reason about a little bit better.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.399
And you end up with a more productive conversation.

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:13.079
So that's non-inferiority testing.

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:15.799
But there's another method that I like that I want to talk to you about.

00:07:15.799 --> 00:07:21.679
And this one directly sort of attacks the core problem, the core question that we have

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:24.519
in these test design conversations.

00:07:24.519 --> 00:07:26.279
And that is...

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:27.279
What's the hurry?

00:07:27.279 --> 00:07:28.279
Right?

00:07:28.279 --> 00:07:31.959
Like, why do we not have the patience to run, like, an adequately powered A-B test in this

00:07:31.959 --> 00:07:32.959
organization?

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:33.959
Right?

00:07:33.959 --> 00:07:34.959
What's going on?

00:07:34.959 --> 00:07:35.959
Why are we in such a rush?

00:07:35.959 --> 00:07:37.359
And we sort of know the answer.

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:38.359
Right?

00:07:38.359 --> 00:07:40.600
Like, running a test a long time is costly.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:42.160
There's an opportunity cost of time.

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.799
This gets back to that, like, the nature of, like, the road mapping and the path dependence

00:07:46.799 --> 00:07:47.799
amongst features.

00:07:47.799 --> 00:07:51.640
If we're waiting a long time for a test of what feature won, that is going to hold up

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:55.239
feature 2, which depends on the launch or the non-launch of feature 1 and what happens.

00:07:55.239 --> 00:07:56.239
Right?

00:07:56.239 --> 00:07:58.880
So a whole load of road maps get held up.

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:02.040
There's the opportunity cost of sampling and randomization and tests.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:03.040
Right?

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:05.839
By construction of an A-B test, a bunch of users are not getting the best version of

00:08:05.839 --> 00:08:06.839
your site.

00:08:06.839 --> 00:08:07.839
Right?

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:10.799
If you've ever worked with bandits or seen bandits, you've seen them trying to approach

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:12.679
this problem.

00:08:12.679 --> 00:08:15.279
And then lastly, there's just, like, the day-to-day maintenance cost of tests.

00:08:15.279 --> 00:08:16.279
Right?

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:18.239
Having a bunch of tests running on the site at once is...

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:21.839
You know, engineering effort and, like, code complexity and data storage and whatever.

00:08:21.839 --> 00:08:22.839
Right?

00:08:22.839 --> 00:08:26.600
Usually that's small, but it's there.

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:27.600
So the question is...

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:28.600
Right?

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:30.640
If we know about all these costs and we know they affect how decision makers want to run

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:35.159
tests, why aren't we incorporating them into test designs?

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:36.320
Right?

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:42.440
And this is where value of information, experimental designs, can help.

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:46.659
So we know the time we spend running a test longer is costly.

00:08:46.659 --> 00:08:49.580
We know the extra data we get from running a test longer is valuable.

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:53.940
If we can quantify the cost and we can quantify the value, that should be telling us how long

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:55.340
we should be running a test.

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:59.380
If the value of more data exceeds the cost of more data, you should keep getting data.

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:03.260
And if the cost of more data exceeds the value of more data, then you should stop getting

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:04.260
data.

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:05.260
Right?

00:09:05.260 --> 00:09:09.340
And it's this picture here.

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:10.340
Right?

00:09:10.340 --> 00:09:15.299
The longer our tests run, the more data we get, the more valuable that data is.

00:09:15.299 --> 00:09:18.380
Experimental data is less valuable when you have a lot than when you have a little.

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:19.380
Right?

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:21.859
Costs increase as you wait to get that data.

00:09:21.859 --> 00:09:26.979
If it's more valuable to get the data than it is costly, you should get the data.

00:09:26.979 --> 00:09:27.979
Right?

00:09:27.979 --> 00:09:31.780
How do we think about the value of data, though?

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:32.780
Right?

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:33.780
What is that?

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:38.539
Well, before we run an experiment, before we have any data, we know very little about

00:09:38.539 --> 00:09:40.260
what the conversion lift of a new feature might be.

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:41.260
It could be very negative.

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:43.340
It could be very positive.

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:49.260
If we make a decision based on our best information now, we could end up launching an awful feature

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.780
or failing to launch a really, really good one.

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:52.780
Right?

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:57.659
And then as we collect data, we have a better idea of what that conversion lift might be,

00:09:57.659 --> 00:10:00.099
the range of values it might take narrows.

00:10:00.099 --> 00:10:05.539
We may make an incorrect guess now, but our guess is likely to be wrong by less.

00:10:05.539 --> 00:10:12.500
And it turns out that you can put a value on being probably less wrong.

00:10:12.659 --> 00:10:17.260
And again, if that value exceeds the cost of the time it takes to get that data, you

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:19.580
should be getting it.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:24.760
So how do we actually, say, like, compute that value, that value of being potentially

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:25.760
less wrong?

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:27.299
It turns out it has a name.

00:10:27.299 --> 00:10:30.099
It's called the expected value of sample information.

00:10:30.099 --> 00:10:35.619
And I'm gonna show you a really simplified way of how you might estimate it.

00:10:35.619 --> 00:10:39.679
So we start with a prior over what we think the conversion lift might be.

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:40.679
Relatively wide range.

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:41.679
We don't know very much.

00:10:41.859 --> 00:10:42.859
It could be negative.

00:10:42.859 --> 00:10:44.659
It could be pretty positive.

00:10:44.659 --> 00:10:49.200
We are going to draw a bunch of values out of that prior, a bunch of potential lifts

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:51.679
out of that prior.

00:10:51.679 --> 00:10:56.239
For each of those lifts that we draw, we're gonna simulate an experiment.

00:10:56.239 --> 00:10:57.239
Right?

00:10:57.239 --> 00:11:00.400
Let's say we're interested in, like, hey, what if I want to get two more weeks of data?

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:01.400
Right?

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:06.000
So I can simulate a two-week experiment, control and treatment with that lift that I drew out

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.719
of the prior.

00:11:07.719 --> 00:11:13.359
That data and that prior generates a posterior with a new opinion about what those lifts

00:11:13.359 --> 00:11:16.159
might be.

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:18.719
Each of those posteriors may change my mind by...

00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:22.299
May not change my mind at all based on what I was gonna do under the prior.

00:11:22.299 --> 00:11:26.960
They may change my mind a lot based on what I was gonna do under the prior.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:29.000
If an experiment generates data...

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:33.400
Is likely to generate data that changes my mind by a lot, that was a valuable experiment

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:34.400
to run.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:35.400
Right?

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:39.080
If the prior had never had any hope of changing my mind, there was no point in doing it.

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:40.080
Right?

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:44.000
And so we run all these simulations, we get all these priors, we get all the posteriors,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.919
we get the values, we average those out.

00:11:45.919 --> 00:11:51.799
That's an estimate of this expected value of getting this extra data.

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:55.159
Even better, this is like an inherently kind of sequential process.

00:11:55.159 --> 00:11:56.159
Right?

00:11:56.159 --> 00:11:57.159
It's just posterior updating.

00:11:57.159 --> 00:11:58.159
So you can do it over and over again.

00:11:58.159 --> 00:12:02.239
After you get some data, you're really just asking, what's the value of some more data?

00:12:02.239 --> 00:12:05.799
And this changes the core decision in an A-B test from...

00:12:05.799 --> 00:12:07.239
Is B better than A?

00:12:07.239 --> 00:12:09.599
As though that's a really hard problem to figure out.

00:12:09.599 --> 00:12:10.599
Right?

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:11.599
To...

00:12:11.599 --> 00:12:12.599
Should I stop getting data?

00:12:12.599 --> 00:12:13.599
Or should I keep getting data?

00:12:13.599 --> 00:12:14.599
Right?

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:15.599
There's a good fit for A-B tests.

00:12:15.599 --> 00:12:17.640
Because we don't have to recruit subjects for an A-B test.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:21.280
We just have to wait.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:25.599
And then once more data isn't worth it, you just launch the best observed variant.

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:30.919
The inference problem, the statistical significance problem is irrelevant at that point.

00:12:30.919 --> 00:12:32.719
This is the best information we have.

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:35.440
And it's not worth getting more.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:36.440
So there you are.

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:41.000
And it turns out, like, I find this a really compelling way to think about A-B tests with

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.159
decision makers.

00:12:43.159 --> 00:12:47.200
It directly gets at the core concepts that they think about when they want to make a

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:48.200
decision.

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:49.200
Right?

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:50.200
Cost.

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:51.200
Benefit.

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:52.200
Time.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:53.200
Risk.

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:54.200
Everything's in dollars.

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:55.200
The outputs are in dollars.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:56.200
Right?

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:57.200
They're not like...

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.200
You know?

00:12:58.200 --> 00:12:59.200
Error rates.

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:00.200
Right?

00:13:00.479 --> 00:13:03.520
So it's more complicated than traditional testing.

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:11.679
But it's tractable for a pretty broad range of the kinds of A-B tests I've run in my experience.

00:13:11.679 --> 00:13:12.679
I've built...

00:13:12.679 --> 00:13:13.679
You know?

00:13:13.679 --> 00:13:14.679
You know?

00:13:14.679 --> 00:13:16.239
There are, like, open research questions on it.

00:13:16.239 --> 00:13:17.760
It's an active area of research still.

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:21.840
But I've built whole analytics engines on it with R and Shiny and worked with product

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:24.039
managers on it who have found it...

00:13:24.039 --> 00:13:25.520
You know?

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:28.559
It gels really well with how they want to make decisions and kind of liberates them

00:13:28.599 --> 00:13:29.599
into being able to...

00:13:29.599 --> 00:13:30.599
Like...

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:34.000
Oh, I can figure out how a test should work with, like, dollar outputs.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.840
Right?

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:40.960
So those are the two methods.

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:45.000
And this is the part of the talk where I'll reveal that I've failed to pay off on the

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.119
clickbait title, per se.

00:13:47.119 --> 00:13:51.159
But hopefully there are some useful lessons.

00:13:51.159 --> 00:13:52.159
So the first one is...

00:13:52.159 --> 00:13:55.119
I'm not trying to sell you on these specific two methods.

00:13:55.119 --> 00:13:59.440
I don't think there's, like, a one-size-fits-all approach to A-B testing.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:02.200
In your organization, you're gonna make decisions differently.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:05.080
You're gonna need to figure out what kind of measurements you need to make to, like,

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:06.080
support those decisions.

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:07.719
These have pros.

00:14:07.719 --> 00:14:08.719
These have cons.

00:14:08.719 --> 00:14:11.200
There's no silver bullet.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:16.000
But when you observe stakeholders misusing the tools that you have provided them to do

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.000
analyses...

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:18.000
Right?

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:23.039
It should really cause you to rethink, oh, what is this tool I've handed to them?

00:14:23.039 --> 00:14:25.000
And does it align with how they make decisions?

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.000
Right?

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:31.559
Does it align with their concerns about risk and cost and time and value and all that important

00:14:31.559 --> 00:14:32.559
stuff?

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:38.479
Am I giving them outputs that map to how they think about the problem?

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:41.919
And when I do that, when I go back and I just try and rethink this, right?

00:14:41.919 --> 00:14:45.320
About the tools that I'm handing them, you really want to get at...

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:49.119
Am I solving the core problem or am I just solving the symptoms of the misuse that I'm

00:14:49.119 --> 00:14:50.119
observing?

00:14:50.119 --> 00:14:51.119
Right?

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:54.599
So, running a test to a neutral, running a test to a significant, peaking.

00:14:54.599 --> 00:14:58.679
All this stuff are kind of a symptom of the problem that the A-B test frameworks we often

00:14:58.679 --> 00:15:04.239
work with don't deal with the cost of time.

00:15:04.239 --> 00:15:07.520
Right?

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:09.359
And there are, like, lots of advanced techniques out there.

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:12.359
There's, like, covariate adjustments, sequential p-values and all this stuff that will run

00:15:12.359 --> 00:15:16.000
out that will help a test go faster.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.880
And they're great and you should use them when you can.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:22.559
But they don't answer the question of, like, why does this test need to go so fast?

00:15:22.559 --> 00:15:26.719
And so they're really just kind of treating the symptom of impatience.

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:27.719
Right?

00:15:27.719 --> 00:15:32.679
And this isn't just about A-B testing, right?

00:15:32.679 --> 00:15:38.619
Data scientists sometimes, like, love a tool and, like, apply it not super discriminantly

00:15:38.619 --> 00:15:39.619
to problems.

00:15:39.619 --> 00:15:43.119
And so we end up with lots of places where the tools we've handed stakeholders aren't

00:15:43.119 --> 00:15:45.919
exactly the perfect fit for how they think about it.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:50.919
A-B testing is a really interesting case, because it's, like, a domain where, you know,

00:15:50.919 --> 00:15:54.239
it feels like this is a solved statistical problem, this should be really straightforward

00:15:54.239 --> 00:16:02.159
and then you go try and use it in practice and it gets messy really fast.

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:06.640
But this is, I think, the cool stuff that we get to do.

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:09.200
This is, like, a vaguely weird time for data scientists.

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:14.919
It feels like a lot of the problems we used to work on are getting automated or outsourced

00:16:14.919 --> 00:16:18.159
or standardized or whatever, right?

00:16:18.159 --> 00:16:22.840
But these kinds of misalignments between decision making in an organization and the data science

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:26.719
tools used to support those decisions happen, like, all over the place and all the time

00:16:26.719 --> 00:16:28.679
in organizations.

00:16:28.679 --> 00:16:33.979
And identifying those and addressing them by, you know, going back to the first principles

00:16:33.979 --> 00:16:38.320
of the problem and really translating that decision making problem into quantitative

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:43.080
methods and quantifying the core concepts in that decision making problem is where we

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:46.239
can, like, add value, right?

00:16:46.239 --> 00:16:50.640
And I don't want you to let, like, SaaS vendors and, like, chat GPT convince you that these

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:52.799
are all solved problems and there's nothing left to do.

00:16:52.799 --> 00:16:56.020
I think there's a lot of things like this to do out there still.

00:16:56.020 --> 00:17:01.479
And I think that's what we're here for, right?

00:17:01.479 --> 00:17:02.479
And that's all I have.

00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:03.479
I hope...

00:17:03.479 --> 00:17:04.479
Thanks for coming, everybody.

00:17:04.479 --> 00:17:05.479
I hope you enjoy the rest of the conference.

00:17:05.479 --> 00:17:06.479
All right.

00:17:06.479 --> 00:17:07.479
Fantastic.

00:17:07.479 --> 00:17:08.479
So...

00:17:08.479 --> 00:17:18.680
Let's see if I can say this correctly.

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:25.359
Is there a risk of compounding poorly tested changes into real deterioration of the project?

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:27.119
So I've got a yes.

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:28.400
But can you talk about that a little bit?

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:29.400
Yeah.

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:30.680
This is asking about the non-inferiority stuff, right?

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:34.040
If you're willing to, like, accept a tiny loss on each test, right?

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:35.640
It starts to add up.

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:36.640
Yes.

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.000
That absolutely can happen.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
I would think...

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:45.640
The way I think about this is having kind of an aggregate inferiority margin budget

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:49.479
over a bunch of tests and going, like, well, you can put a margin on this one and this

00:17:49.479 --> 00:17:51.680
one and this one, but you can't, like...

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:55.839
You know, this is, like, the total loss that we can kind of accept over, like, a long sequence

00:17:55.839 --> 00:17:58.400
of tests or for a year or over some unit of time.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:00.839
And so you have to, like, sort of budget out that risk that you're...

00:18:00.839 --> 00:18:03.920
You should have a risk budget for all these decisions, right?

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.800
You don't want to think about them in isolation, right?

00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:07.800
Okay.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:08.800
Fantastic.

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:09.800
Let's thank Carl again.

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:10.800
Thank you.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:10.800


